Danny Hillis is an inventor, scientist, author and engineer. While completing his doctorate at MIT, he pioneered the concept of parallel computers that is now the basis for graphics processors and cloud computing. He holds more than 300 US patents, covering parallel computers, disk arrays, forgery prevention methods, various electronic and mechanical devices, and the pinch-to-zoom display interface. He has recently been working on problems in medicine as well. He is also the designer of a 10,000-year mechanical clock, and he gave a TED Talk in 1994 that is practically prophetic. Throughout his career, Hillis has worked at places like Disney, and now MIT and Applied Invention, always looking for the next fascinating problem.

author: Danny_Hillis;
title: The Internet could crash. We need a Plan B

aws-transcripts.transcript: So this book that I have in my hand is a directory of everybody who had an email address in 1982. Um, actually, it's deceptively large. There's actually only about 20 people on each page because we have the name, address and telephone number of every single person. And in fact, everybody is listed twice because it's sorted once by name and once by email address, obviously a very small community. There were only two other Danny's on the Internet then I knew them both. We didn't all know each other, but we all kind of trusted each other. And that basic feeling of trust so permeated the whole network. And there was a really sense that we could depend on each other to do things. So just to give you an idea of the level of trust in this community, let me tell you what it was like to register a domain name in the early days. Now it just so happened that I got to register the third domain name on the Internet so I could have anything I wanted other than bbn dot com and symbolic dot com. So I picked think dot com, but then I thought, you know, there's a lot of really interesting names out there. Maybe I should register a few extras just just in case. And then I thought, No, that wouldn't be very nice. Um, that that attitude of only taking what you need was really what everybody had on the network in those days.
